Project- 3 : Thera Bank Modelling¶

Submitted By : Aman Kumar Agarwal¶

Question¶

This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) which has a growing customer base. Majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying size of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns to better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

The department wants to build a model that will help them identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan. This will increase the success ratio while at the same time reduce the cost of the campaign.

Column descriptions¶

ID : Customer ID
Age : Customer's age in completed years
Experience : years of professional experience
Income : Annual income of the customer
ZIPCode: Home Address ZIP code.
Family : Family size of the customer
CCAvg Avg. : spending on credit cards per month
Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional
Mortgage : Value of house mortgage if any.
Personal Loan : Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
Securities Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
CD Account : Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
Online : Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
CreditCard : Does the customer uses a credit card issued by UniversalBank?

Building The Model¶

Identifying the Independent (Feature) variables and Dependent (Target) variables.¶

In [46]:
# Due to the high co-relation of 0.99 between Age and Experience, the Age column is not considered in model building.
# Also, ZIP Code doesn't play an important role.
# Personal Loan is the target variable

independent = ['Experience','Income','Family','CCAvg',
               'Education_1','Education_2','Education_3',
               'Mortgage','Securities Account','CD Account',
                'Online','CreditCard']

dependent =  'Personal Loan'
X = bank[independent]
y = np.array(bank[dependent])

score_LR=[]

    X_bar_train,X_bar_test,y_bar_train,y_bar_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.30)

    score_LR.append(iterative_LR.score(X_bar_test,y_bar_test))

--------------------------------------K-NN-------------------------------------------------------¶

We first run a single iteration of the model with a random seed and then perform multiple iterations to get an average accuracy score.¶

In KNN, since it is a distance based algorithm, the standardization of the independent variables by using statistical techniques such as zscore is a good practice so that the algorithm doesn't get biased with the different range of values in different attributes.¶

In [65]:
#Standardizing training set
def standardize_train(X):

    KNN_XT = pd.DataFrame()
    KNN_XT['Experience'] =zscore(X_train['Experience'])
    KNN_XT['Income'] =zscore(X_train['Income'])
    KNN_XT['Family'] =zscore(X_train['Family'])
    KNN_XT['CCAvg'] =zscore(X_train['CCAvg'])
    KNN_XT['Education_1'] =zscore(X_train['Education_1'])
    KNN_XT['Education_2'] =zscore(X_train['Education_2'])
    KNN_XT['Education_3'] =zscore(X_train['Education_3'])
    KNN_XT['Mortgage'] =zscore(X_train['Mortgage'])
    KNN_XT['Securities Account'] =zscore(X_train['Securities Account'])
    KNN_XT['CD Account'] =zscore(X_train['CD Account'])
    KNN_XT['Online'] =zscore(X_train['Online'])
    KNN_XT['CreditCard'] =zscore(X_train['CreditCard'])
    return KNN_XT
In [66]:
#Standardizing test set
def standardize_test(X):
    KNN_XT2 = pd.DataFrame()
    KNN_XT2['Experience'] =zscore(X_test['Experience'])
    KNN_XT2['Income'] =zscore(X_test['Income'])
    KNN_XT2['Family'] =zscore(X_test['Family'])
    KNN_XT2['CCAvg'] =zscore(X_test['CCAvg'])
    KNN_XT2['Education_1'] =zscore(X_test['Education_1'])
    KNN_XT2['Education_2'] =zscore(X_test['Education_2'])
    KNN_XT2['Education_3'] =zscore(X_test['Education_3'])
    KNN_XT2['Mortgage'] =zscore(X_test['Mortgage'])
    KNN_XT2['Securities Account'] =zscore(X_test['Securities Account'])
    KNN_XT2['CD Account'] =zscore(X_test['CD Account'])
    KNN_XT2['Online'] =zscore(X_test['Online'])
    KNN_XT2['CreditCard'] =zscore(X_test['CreditCard'])
    return KNN_XT2

Running multiple iterations of the model (Standardized) to get the average accuracy.¶

Here, no random seed is used to cover the variance in the dataset¶

In [96]:
score_KNN=[]
for i in range(10):
    X_bar_train,X_bar_test,y_bar_train,y_bar_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.30)
    KNN_X_train = standardize_train(X_bar_train)
    KNN_X_test = standardize_test(X_bar_test)
    iterative_KNN = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=17, weights='distance')
    iterative_KNN.fit(KNN_X_train,y_bar_train)
    score_KNN.append(iterative_KNN.score(KNN_X_test,y_bar_test))

Conlusion¶

  1. The dataset has no missing values.
  2. Family size does not have quite a good effect on the personal loan, however family of sizes 3 and 4 have slightly more chance of taking a loan. This can be used in future campaigns.
  3. The undergrads have the least conversion rate. The target audience is more towards the Graduates and Proffessionals.
  4. Most of the poeple have not taken mortgage.
  5. Almost everyone with a CD account has a loan. Can be used to target customers with CD accounts.
  6. People who accepted personal loan, belong to the higher income bracket.
  7. Education level 1 have relatively higher income than other education levels.
  8. Income of all loan takers in different education levels are nearly same.
  9. People who have higher monthly credit card expenses, are more likely to accept personal loans.
  10. Customers who have high mortgage value tend to apply more for personal loans.
  11. Age and experience have a direct co-relation (0.99).
  12. Naive Bayes model gives the lowest accuracy of 89%.
  13. Logistic Regression gives one of the highest accuracy of 96%.
  14. K nearest Neighbors gives an average accuracy of 90.50%
  15. Support Vector machines also prove to give good amount of accuracy. However the various kernels give different accuracy.
  16. SVM with Linear kernel proves to give one of the highest accuracies of 96.50%.
  17. As Logistic Regression gives 96% accuracy, and SVM with a linear kernel also gives high accuracy, it can be said that the given data works best with linear classification models. That is why we have high accuracies in both cases. Therefore a Logistic Regression model should be used as for a pure linear model.
  18. The bank can make use of certain factors such as the customer's Education Levels to target a potential customer.
  19. Also, good attention must be given to the customers with certificate of deposit (CD) accounts has they have the highest conversion rate of 60%.
  20. The bank should therefore use a linear model such as Logistic Regression to target potential customers to increase their personal loan conversion rate.
